segments.text: Cross Jr., head of the Department of Aerospace Engineering.
Today's date is July 24th.
Dr. Cross, would you discuss your boyhood years?
Born and raised in a small town in central Pennsylvania called Mill Hall.
Went to high school three miles away in Lock Haven, Pennsylvania.
Graduated from high school in 1948 and went to Penn State.
Where is Penn State?
State College.
What's the name of the city?
State College is the name of the city.
Stayed there two years and entered the Air Force.
Alright, before you go on that, would you tell us about your parents?
Parents were both born and raised on farms.
My mother was a housewife.
She had gone to
the local teacher's college and graduated from that and was a certified teacher.
My dad worked for Slovenia Electric Company most of the time, quit after I left high school and entered into his own business.
What about brothers and sisters?
One sister, younger.
Where does she live today?
She lives in Reading, Pennsylvania.
When you went to Penn State, you studied aerospace engineering?
No, physics.
Physics.
You got your bachelor's degree in physics.
No, just two years in physics.
Would you discuss that?
In what sense?
I stayed at Penn State only two years.
and studied physics.
The Korean War was in the middle of its biggest flap.
I left and joined the Air Force as an aviation cadet.
Where were you stationed during this time?
I went to flight school in Columbus, Mississippi and Enid, Oklahoma.
How long were you in the Air Force?
Twenty-two years.
You stayed in straight through?
Stayed in straight through.
Alright, what about your bachelor's degree?
I returned to Penn State as an Air Force student in 57 after having flown for four and a half years and finished a bachelor's degree in aerospace, really aeronautical engineering in 59.
What about your graduate work?
Well, following the bachelor's degree, I was assigned to the 10-foot Trans-Sonic Wind Tunnel at Wright Field.
Where?
Wright Field, Wright-Patterson Air Force Base in Dayton, Ohio.
I was there for about four years, and Ohio State had a local
part of the university graduate school, which I attended after duty hours.
The Air Force sent me off again in 62 to the University of Texas for graduate school, and I finally finished both an M.S.
and a Ph.D. at the University of Texas.
What year did you finish the Ph.D.?
What was the subject of your dissertation?
It involved the lee-side flow field of a sharp-edged delta wing, really a series of delta wings, at hypersonic Mach numbers.
It was an experimental study, primarily.
Did a series of wind tunnel tests

a small tunnel we had at the Aerospace Research Laboratories in Dayton and also a series of studies in the I guess it was a four-foot hypersonic tunnel in the Arnold Air Development Center in Tallahoma, Tennessee.
Can you tell us about your family?
Married
Judy Wanker, galley dated in high school after flight school.
Spell that last name.
W-E-N-K-E-R. Do you have children?
Six.
Six children.
Three boys, three girls, ranging in age now from 27 through 17.
All right.
You left the Air Force in 1972.
Three.
What did you do then?
I became the director, well I went to Mississippi State University as a professor of aerospace engineering and director of the Raspid Flight Research Laboratory.
Did you spell the name of that?
R-A-S-P-E-T. How long did you stay there?
Six years.
Did you stay there until 79 when you came to A&M as head of the Department of Aerospace Engineering?
Yeah, I came here in July of 79.
What was the name of the department head before you came here?
There was an interim department head, Stan Lowy, and prior to him Al Kronk who had been the department head since I think the late 60s.
Did you spell those last names there?
Yes, Stan Lowy is L-O-W-Y and Al Kronk is C-R-O-N-K. What are some of the duties that you undertake as department head?
I'm responsible for the administration of the academic program and the research program.
The academic program includes the budgets and planning and growth development of the faculty, also the development of the graduate program.
responsible for the daily or the day-by-day administrative duties, which there are uncounted ones of.
Or do you teach any classes?
I teach regularly typically one class.
In what?
Aerodynamics.
Could you discuss the number of faculty members that you supervise and where some of the schools that these faculty members are from?
Okay, right now we have, let's see, 17.
Ohio State, I guess, is the dominant school.
We have three from Ohio State, one from Rutgers,
I'm from the University of Texas.
Well, there are two others from the University of Texas.
So we have three from UT.
Two from Mississippi State.
One from Illinois.
Let's see.
One from MIT.
All right.
What is the size of the aerospace engineering program here compared to the other engineering programs?
Relative to the other engineering programs at A&M, we're right in the middle of the ten.
About how many students do you have enrolled?
We have about 550 undergraduates expect in the fall.
That's fall of 81.
We'll have over 600, which makes us probably the largest aero department in the country.
The largest what?
The largest aero department in the country.
Oh, okay.
About how many graduate students did you say you said?
No, we're deficient in the graduate student area.
We're having a dreadful time of tracking them.
We've got right now about 20.
And you have both of the graduate degrees offered here?
We offer MS, ME, DE, and PhD.
Why is it difficult to attract graduate students into aerospace engineering?
They're getting very lucrative offers from industry with promise of company subsidized graduate studies on site.
And that appears much more attractive than anything we can offer.
That's a major limitation in our research program too.
During the 1970s, as I understand it, there was a major slump in aerospace engineering all over the country.
Could you discuss that?
There was.
Actually, it started in the 60s and continued into the middle 70s.
The major source of the thing came about as a wind down of the Vietnamese war, I believe, since the aerospace industry is very closely coupled with DOD budget.
But we've been slowly recovering to the point now where I think we've exceeded, at least in terms of undergraduate enrollment, the level we had reached during the late 60s.
Historically, the aerospace industry has been cyclical.
There's been some effort by government to eliminate the peaks and the valleys.
I'm not real sure if that's going to happen.
But aerospace engineers are being used in more and more types of industry now, not so tightly tied to the aerospace industries.
So engineers with aerospace engineering degrees can get jobs in related fields?

They can get jobs in a whole range of fields which are just starting to recognize some of the things that aerospace engineers are particularly good at and that's lightweight structures, control systems, things that involve fluid flows,
and more recently the transportation industry has been hiring aerospace engineers.
Okay, could you explain in layman's terms what an aerospace engineer does on the job?
Oh boy, there's a whole range of things he does.
Typically the young engineer that is one right fresh out of the university with a bachelor's degree
We'll wind up working for a senior engineer, and he'll serve primarily as the interface between the senior engineer and the computer terminal.
And slowly he'll be worked into involvement in more significant kinds of problems.
We maintain that our engineers are trained principally as designers.
and expect that they'll be involved in the design process.
They're also well suited for not necessarily research, but the kinds of things that are categorized as experimental development or exploratory development.

and projects which involve development of the technology relative to the technology which is pertinent to the product, either an aerospace system or whatever the company happens to be producing, automobiles maybe.
OK. Of about 550 students that you have, about how many of them are women?
Last semester we had twelve percent.
Twelve percent.
So sixty.
Alright, about what percent are black?
Less than one percent.
Why is it difficult to attract blacks to engineering programs?
I don't really know.
If I did know, I would have more.
What about foreign students?
We have very few foreign students in either the graduate program or the undergraduate program.
We have currently two foreign students out of about 20 in the graduate program, and I'm not real sure how many in the undergraduate program.
Well, some of the other engineering programs attract a good many foreign students, so why would it be that this aerospace didn't attract as many as some of the others?
Well, the program does attract a lot.
We don't admit many.
Okay.
What about your admissions standard?
Can you talk about that in the graduate program?
The graduate program admissions are pretty much a function of departmental
policy, our control mechanism really is tied to fellowships, research assistantships, teaching assistantships, things of that sort.
We have a lot of applicants that are in fact qualified for entry that never come because we don't offer an assistantship to them.
What do you go by to decide who gets offered an assistantship?
It's pretty much on the basis of quality, and the quality criteria is associated with undergraduate GPR.
We look for undergraduate GPRs well in excess of three, and also GRE scores.
We like to see the GRE scores in excess of 1,100.
What salary does a beginning aerospace engineer with a bachelor's degree usually expect to receive?
This past spring they were receiving typically $23,000.
What about someone with more experience and a graduate degree, what would they expect?
A master's degree was typically being offered $26,000, $27,000.
and a PhD, $33,000 nominally.
Is there still a problem with aerospace engineers having difficulty finding positions the way it was earlier?
No.
All of our graduates at all levels have had multiple offers, and it's been a matter of selecting the one that was most appealing to them.
I know at one time, particularly in the Seattle area, there was a problem with aerospace engineers who couldn't find jobs.

do you know anything about that up there how that situation's been alleviated yeah the situation has been alleviated I don't know if it's been cured the Seattle aerospace industry is a one company operation that's Boeing and when Boeing has problems and the Seattle-based aerospace engineers have problems right now Boeing is very very healthy
How do you find the quality of your undergraduate students?
The quality of the entering freshmen is typically not very good.
And we've found that of an entering freshman class, we'll probably only graduate somewhere between 25% and 35%.
So it's very inefficient.
And most of these, you think, drop out or they go to other fields of engineering or what?
I think most of them leave engineering.
Typically they're poorly counseled and poorly prepared by their high schools.
So most leave engineering.
Some transfer to other engineering disciplines.
Could it be that they enter the program without understanding what aerospace engineering actually is?
They enter the program with a fuzzy understanding of what engineering is.
and some mistaken notion about what aerospace is really all about.
You find the quality of the graduate students greater compared to the undergraduates?
The quality of the graduate students is not as high as I would like to see it, but it's considerably better than the undergraduate.
We have better control over the graduate program than we do the undergraduate.
What about your research duties here?
Can you discuss the research program?
Okay, I'm head of the Aerospace Engineering Division of TEAS.
And I have essentially the same kinds of responsibilities in the research side as I do in the academic side.
That is, I'm responsible for preparing budgets and plans and the daily routine of administrative responsibilities, responsible for recruiting
competent research people, competent research support people.
I'm directly responsible for the 7 foot by 10 foot low speed wind tunnel, and also the flight mechanics laboratory at the research center.
And more recently, I guess, a 6 by 6 foot environmental wind
I'm responsible for the overall maintenance of an adequate level of activity in the research of aerodynamic or aerospace-related topics.
Where do you do the research here?
What part of the campus is this done on?
The wind tunnel is at Easterwood Airport.
The flight mechanics lab is at the research center.
at the old Bryan Air Force Base.
The other major facility we utilize is the mainframe computer at the data processing center.
So those that are involved in experimental research are typically working off campus.
Those that are involved in theoretical research are primarily working on the campus.
Do the faculty members divide their time equally between teaching and research?
It depends.
We target senior faculty for 50% research during the academic year and 100% during the summers, which amounts to a total research activity of about 67%.
The junior faculty, in a break, occurs someplace in a guy's professional development
as an associate professor.
The junior faculty, we expect to be involved in 25% research during the academic year and 100% during the summers, which amounts to something like 48% overall split.
But involvement in research implies outside support.
We have only very limited resources to subsidize research.
The money we have we spend typically in support of preliminary research activity by junior faculty leading to hopefully development of a proposal and support from some outside agency.
What are some of the sources of your funding for the research program?
It comes from all over.

I guess the major sources are NASA at several research centers, DOD, the National Science Foundation, a whole range of companies that contract with us for various kinds of research, architectural companies, aircraft companies,
some energy companies or oil companies.
What about state legislative funding?
Does that finance some of the research?
Yeah.
It supports the research to the extent that we can pay those kinds of people that
support the researchers.
As an example, we have an A&P mechanic at the flight level.
We pay his salary out of state money.
25% of my salary is paid out of state money.
We pay our secretary out of state money.
And we'll also support young faculty in the development of their research program.

you consider the state legislative funding adequate or is more needed i think it's adequate you can always use more what has happened in this department is that there's been an inadequate investment historically say going back 15 years there's been a woefully inadequate investment in capital equipment

The capital equipment that was here 15 years ago has been depleted because of inadequate investment in maintenance and update, so that now our capability, particularly in the experimental area, is seriously limited by inadequate equipment.
What was the reason the equipment was
not properly invested into?
I think primarily due to inattention.
Sir?
Inattention.
Nobody was paying attention to what was going on and what was required.
That combined with the fact that during that period, I guess the majority of the research involved theoretical things.
It isn't peculiar to Texas A&M.

I think it's been typically the case where many universities, particularly state universities, state-endowed universities, have depleted their capital resources over the last 15 or 20 years to the point now where laboratory equipment, particularly research equipment and facilities, have been virtually totally depleted
And we're faced now with a monster problem of replacing those things at prices that are orders of magnitude higher than they had been.
That's going to be a long time and difficult period to correct these things.
Okay.
Tell us something more specifically about particular research projects that are now underway.
Okay.
Let's see, starting with the theoretical activity.
I guess Lee Carlson is the shiny one exactly right now.
He's been involved for many years and is still active in the research of transonic airfoil development.
That's been extended or expanded now to include three-dimensional aspects of that problem.
He's been funded by NASA Langley for six, eight years in that area.
He's also involved in a massive separation
problem for three-dimensional wings that are approaching stalled conditions.
He's also been involved in a balloon, a large
scientific balloon analyses which involved a float condition for these things, funded out of Wallops Research Center, which is a piece of NASA.
Dave Norton is an experimentalist, so I guess I shouldn't jump onto him right away.
Walt Hasler, another very strong theoretical...
Spell that last name.
Hasler, H-A-I-S-L-E-R, has been involved for many years in applications of finite element methods to the constitutive modeling of materials and analyses of various kinds of structures.
Let's see, what else do we have?
David Allen has recently come on board.
He will become active also in that research area.
Dave Norton has been very active in the area of environmental aerodynamics, which is primarily an experimental
a continuing experimental study of the wind effects on architectural structures, new buildings, offshore oil rigs, things of that sort.
Stan Miley has been active.
Say that last night, please.

Stan Miley, M-I-L-E-Y, an associate professor, been here two years, has been active in a theoretical study of the influence of a propeller slipstream on forces generated by wings, nacelles, and aircraft fuselages.
primarily interested in the interaction of those three aircraft components in the propeller slipstream.
He's also been active in the study of low Reynolds number airfoils in application to windmills and power generation.
Howard Chevalier has been active in wind tunnel studies and flight test studies of stall prevention systems, or the general problem of stall prevention in general aviation aircraft.
He's also been recently involved in wind tunnel studies of various aircraft configurations.
in particular forward sweep of wings and canard surfaces.
That's all I can think of right now.
So you entered the University of Teaching in 1973 at Mississippi State.
Yeah.
Have you seen any change in just those eight years that you've been involved in
What changes have you seen in the aerospace program, even though taking into account that there are two institutions involved here that you've been in?
Yeah, the really big change has involved the increased application of computer methods to all phases of the thing, and in particular the use of computers in design.
We're just now making a sizable investment in computers for use in systems design, particularly aircraft design.
We have a series of three courses in design of structures, propulsion, and aircraft.
And we'll be using the computer more and more in connection with the sizable investments required.
That's one of the areas in which there's been an inadequate university investment.
Not peculiar to A&M, but most universities have fallen into that trap.
Have you seen any change in the quality of the students during those eight years?
Yeah, there has been, I think, kind of an anomaly occur in that we're getting more and more of the really super good students, but we're also getting more and more of the not so super good students.
So the tail ends of the distribution of student quality is moving out in both directions.
But we are getting more and more of the really good students.
That's the same observation that Dr. Jones in electrical engineering had found, what you just said.
I interviewed him.
He found the same situation.
The so-called poor students, what are their deficiencies in?
Mathematics and the physical sciences and motivation.
You mentioned this.
new investment needed in the computer.
Are there any new facilities being planned for aerospace engineering here?
Not specifically for aerospace engineering, but there is a committee, or maybe several committees, that's looking very carefully at the computer problem in particular.
And whatever they do will have a major impact on aerospace engineering.
I don't really know precisely where the whole thing is headed, but whatever they do is going to have a major impact in our program.
Is aerospace engineering going to be in this building you're in now indefinitely?
Yes, we've been here since I guess 54 or so when the building was new.
There's a minor
renovation occurring in the building now, and we'll relocate to the second floor in the fall, but we'll be in this building for the next 180 years or so.
What other departments are in this building?

The business college just moved out in June, leaving engineering design graphics on the third floor, sharing the middle floor with us, and there's a small piece of parks and recreation in the other end of the middle floor.
What do you think are some of the challenges that aerospace engineers can look for in the 1980s?
Oh, boy.
I guess the major challenge involves the impact of the energy situation on transportation in general, but in particular aircraft.
It also impacts such things as the automotive industry.
And there have been more and more space engineers involved in working that problem.
That seems to me to be the major challenge, the development of transportation systems which are energy efficient.
Prior to 1975 or whenever it was that
that the OPEC countries first lowered the boom on us, the major emphasis was on performance rather than energy efficiency.
Now that has swung completely around the other way to the point where energy efficiency is the primary concern, with maybe the possible exception of defense-related systems.
What is the best that you personally expect for an energy efficient engine to get, say for an automobile?
The best performance?
That's really difficult to put a number on because it's a combination of the engine with the device, whatever it is, an automobile or a truck or a bus.
Now in regard to say commuter type automobiles they're talking in terms of 75 miles per gallon within the next several years.
You think that's realistic?
Yeah, yeah I believe it is.
You might not like the vehicle but I believe you can get 75 miles per gallon.
But you mentioned earlier that Texas A&M had one of the largest aerospace engineering programs in the country.
Would you elaborate on that?
I think it is the largest undergraduate aerospace program in the country.
And this program was established in 1940.
Is that about the time that most of the others were established across the country, or is that a little later or earlier?
I think that's just about the same time most of them are popping up, 1938, 39, 40, and on through the 40s.
Then during the 60s, a lot of aero departments were combined with other departments because of low enrollment and things of that sort.
So you'll find a lot of aerospace and mechanical engineering departments around the country.
What would be the next largest aerospace programs after Texas A&M?
Penn State has the next, as far as I know, undergraduate program.
Our graduate program is not anywhere near the largest, and I'm not really sure who has the largest aerospace graduate program.
Purdue also has a large, large department.
Why do you think aerospace engineering doesn't attract as many students as some of the other engineering fields?
There isn't as big a market for aerospace engineers as say mechanical or electrical and the enrollment kind of seeks its own level
based on the marketability of the particular degree.
Typically, we attract students that are enthused by airplanes and or the space program, things of that sort.
Since the shuttle success, I expect to see an increase in our enrollment.
Was Texas A&M involved in space shuttle research?
Yeah, since about

The date is uncertain, but we have been involved in the development of the configuration through wind tunnel tests, also involved in an evaluation of the damage tolerance of the tile system, and maybe some other lesser things.
We're now involved in the development of a system to de-ice the main tank.
of the launch vehicle.
The fuel was liquid hydrogen.
And whilst it's sitting on the pad, it accumulates a significant amount of ice.
And during the launch sequence, that ice breaks loose and damages the tile.
So NASA's interested in de-icing the tank whilst it's on the pad.
And then you expect the space shuttle
promote more research in this field in aerospace engineering.
Oh, sure.
Yeah, it'll be a continuing thing.
Is there anything else that you'd like to say before we close?
Don't think so.
I believe that's about all I know to ask you.
I appreciate you taking the time to talk with me.
Okay.
Thank you.
